<h2 id="org2a2340f">Airbnb Tips <a href="../../../Notes/720_airbnb-20251128205545.html#ID-76417A76-CB65-42B3-82F7-56A04866B879">720 Airbnb</a></h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org2a2340f">
<p>
<a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/AirBnB/comments/13q7jr2/hosts_what_do_you_wish_you_knew_when_you_were/">https://www.reddit.com/r/AirBnB/comments/13q7jr2/hosts_what_do_you_wish_you_knew_when_you_were/</a>
-) Stand firm on your pricing - we're not in a bazaar. It's often a red flag if someone is trying to haggle, with perhaps the exception of long-term stays.
-) Develop a set of canned responses in Airbnb to answer frequent questions efficiently. This will save you a ton of time.
-) Be meticulous with your listing details - it helps to minimize the barrage of queries.
-) Invest in high-quality photos. They’re your property’s first impression, and it truly makes a difference.
-) It's completely reasonable to ask prospective guests about their group composition. Adding a personal touch can create a welcoming environment. For instance, if a family is coming, I like to leave some sweets, or if it's a group of surfers, a chilled soda is usually appreciated.
</p>
